                        <span class="active">The Bridge Builder</span>
                     </li>
        </ul>
                            <ul class="prev-next large"><li class="prev"><a href="http://lds.org/ensign/2003/11/the-shepherds-of-israel?lang=eng">Previous</a></li><li class="next"><a href="http://lds.org/ensign/2003/11/the-grandeur-of-god?lang=eng">Next</a></li></ul>
                            
                            
                            <h1>
                            The Bridge Builder
                            </h1>
                            <h2 class="author">
                                    <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/thomas-s-monson?lang=eng"><div class="byline" id="">
				<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p3" class="">President Thomas S. Monson</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p" class="">First Counselor in the First Presidency</p>
			</div></a>   
                                    </h2>
                            <hr>
                        </div><!-- end #details -->
                       
                        <div id="primary">
                            
                            
                            <blockquote class="intro dontHighlight">
                                        <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/thomas-s-monson?lang=eng">
                                                        <img id="talkPhoto" src="/bc/content/shared/content/images/leaders/thomas-s-monson-10.jpg" alt="Thomas S. Monson" class="img-decor">
                                                    </a>
                                        
                                        <div class="kicker" id="">Jesus Christ &hellip; has built the bridges over which we must cross if we are to reach our heavenly home.</div>
                                        
                                    </blockquote>
                            <span style="display: none" id="article-id">23911_000_022</span>
			<div class="figure">
				
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p5" class="">Many years ago I read a book entitled <span class="emphasis">The Way to the Western Sea,</span> by David S. Lavender. It provides a fascinating account of the epic journey of Meriwether Lewis and William Clark as they led their famed expedition across the North American continent to discover an overland route to the Pacific Ocean.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p6" class="">Their trek was a nightmare of backbreaking toil, deep gorges which had to be crossed, and extensive travel by foot, carrying with them their supply-laden boats to find the next stream on which to make their way.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p7" class="">As I read of their experiences, I frequently mused, &ldquo;If only there were modern bridges to span the gorges of the raging waters.&rdquo; There came to my mind thoughts of magnificent bridges of our time which accomplish this task with ease: beautiful Golden Gate Bridge of San Francisco fame; sturdy Sydney, Australia, Harbour Bridge; and others in many lands.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p8" class="">In reality, we are all travelers&mdash;even explorers of mortality. We do not have the benefit of previous personal experience. We must pass over steep precipices and turbulent waters in our own journey here on earth.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p9" class="">Perhaps such a somber thought inspired the poet Will Allen Dromgoole&rsquo;s classic poem entitled &ldquo;The Bridge Builder.&rdquo;</p>
			<div class="figure">
				<div class="stanza" id="">
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">An old man, going a lone highway,</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">Came at the evening, cold and gray,</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">To a chasm, vast and deep and wide,</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">Through which was flowing a sullen tide.</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">The old man crossed in the twilight dim;</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">The sullen stream had no fears for him;</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">But he turned when safe on the other side</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">And built a bridge to span the tide.</span>
	  </div>
				</div>
				<div class="stanza" id="">
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">&ldquo;Old man,&rdquo; said a fellow pilgrim near,</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">&ldquo;You are wasting strength with building here;</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">Your journey will end with the ending day;</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">You never again must pass this way;</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">You have crossed the chasm, deep and wide&mdash;</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">Why build you the bridge at the eventide?&rdquo;</span>
	  </div>
				</div>
				<div class="stanza" id="">
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">The builder lifted his old gray head:</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">&ldquo;Good friend, in the path I have come,&rdquo; he said,</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">&ldquo;There followeth after me today</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">A youth whose feet must pass this way.</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">This chasm that has been naught to me</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">To that fair-haired youth may a pitfall be.</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">He, too, must cross in the twilight dim;</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">Good friend, I am building the bridge for him.&rdquo;</span>
	    <sup class="noteMarker">
	    <a href="#footnote1-23911_000_022">1</a>
	  </sup>
	  </div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p32" class="">The message of the poem has prompted my thinking and comforted my soul, for our Lord and Savior, <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/jesus-christ">Jesus Christ</a>, was the supreme architect and builder of bridges for you, for me, for all mankind. He has built the bridges over which we must cross if we are to reach our heavenly home.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p33" class="">The Savior&rsquo;s mission was foretold. Matthew recorded, &ldquo;And she shall bring forth a son, and thou shalt call his name Jesus: for he shall save his people from their sins.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote2-23911_000_022">2</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p34" class="">There followed the miracle of His birth and the gathering of the shepherds who came with haste to that stable, to that mother, to that child. Even the Wise Men, journeying from the East, followed that star and bestowed their precious gifts upon the young child.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p35" class="">The scripture records that Jesus &ldquo;grew, and waxed strong in spirit, filled with wisdom: and the grace of God was upon him&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote3-23911_000_022">3</a>
      </sup> and that He &ldquo;went about doing good.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote4-23911_000_022">4</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p36" class="">What personal bridges did He build and cross here in mortality, showing us the way to follow? He knew mortality would be filled with dangers and difficulties. He declared: &ldquo;Come unto me, all ye that labour and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest. Take my yoke upon you, and learn of me; for I am meek and lowly in heart: and ye shall find rest unto your souls. For my yoke is easy, and my burden is light.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote5-23911_000_022">5</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p37" class="">Jesus provided the <span class="strong">Bridge of Obedience.</span> He was an unfailing example of personal obedience as He kept the commandments of His Father.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p38" class="">When He was led of the Spirit into the wilderness to be tempted of Satan, He was weak from fasting. Satan was at his seductive best in the offerings he proffered. His first was to satisfy the Savior&rsquo;s physical needs, including His hunger. To this the Savior replied, &ldquo;It is written, Man shall not live by bread alone, but by every word that proceedeth out of the mouth of God.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote6-23911_000_022">6</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p39" class="">Next Satan offered power. Responded the Savior, &ldquo;It is written again, Thou shalt not tempt the Lord thy God.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote7-23911_000_022">7</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p40" class="">Finally the Savior was offered wealth and earthly glory. His response: &ldquo;Get thee hence, Satan: for it is written, Thou shalt worship the Lord thy God, and him only shalt thou serve.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote8-23911_000_022">8</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p41" class="">The Apostle Paul was inspired of the Lord to declare for our time, as well as for his: &ldquo;There hath no temptation taken you but such as is common to man: but God is faithful, who will not suffer you to be tempted above that ye are able; but will with the temptation also make a way to escape, that ye may be able to bear it.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote9-23911_000_022">9</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p42" class="">Lest we equivocate, I mention a comment from ABC <span class="emphasis">Nightline</span>&rsquo;s Ted Koppel: &ldquo;What <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/ensign/1998/04/moses-witness-of-jesus-christ?lang=eng">Moses</a> brought down from Mt. Sinai were not the Ten Suggestions [but the Ten] Commandments!&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote10-23911_000_022">10</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p43" class="">A bit of subtle humor is found in an account of a conversation between Mark Twain and a friend. Said the wealthy friend to Twain, &ldquo;Before I die, I mean to make a pilgrimage to the Holy Land. I will climb to the top of Mount Sinai and read the Ten Commandments aloud.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p44" class="">Replied Twain, &ldquo;Why don&rsquo;t you stay home and keep them!&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p45" class="">The second bridge provided by the Master for us to cross is the <span class="strong">Bridge of Service.</span> We look to the Savior as our example of service. Although He came to earth as the Son of God, He humbly served those around Him. He came forth from heaven to live on earth as mortal man and to establish the kingdom of God. His glorious gospel reshaped the thinking of the world. He blessed the sick; He caused the lame to walk, the blind to see, the deaf to hear. He even raised the dead to life.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p46" class="">In the 25th chapter of the book of Matthew, the Savior tells us this concerning the faithful who will be on His right hand at His triumphal return:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p47" class="">&ldquo;Then shall the King say unto them &hellip; , Come, ye blessed of my Father, inherit the kingdom prepared for you from the foundation of the world:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p48" class="">&ldquo;For I was an hungred, and ye gave me meat: I was thirsty, and ye gave me drink: I was a stranger, and ye took me in:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p49" class="">&ldquo;Naked, and ye clothed me: I was sick, and ye visited me: I was in prison, and ye came unto me.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p50" class="">&ldquo;Then shall the righteous answer him, saying, Lord, when saw we thee an hungred, and fed thee? or thirsty, and gave thee drink?</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p51" class="">&ldquo;When saw we thee a stranger, and took thee in? or naked, and clothed thee?</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p52" class="">&ldquo;Or when saw we thee sick, or in prison, and came unto thee?</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p53" class="">&ldquo;And the King shall answer and say unto them, Verily I say unto you, Inasmuch as ye have done it unto one of the least of these my brethren, ye have done it unto me.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote11-23911_000_022">11</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p54" class="">Elder Richard L. Evans once counseled, &ldquo;We can&rsquo;t do everything for everyone everywhere, but we can do something for someone somewhere.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote12-23911_000_022">12</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p55" class="">May I share with you an account of an opportunity of service which came to me unexpectedly and in an unusual manner. I received a telephone call from a granddaughter of an old friend. She asked, &ldquo;Do you remember Francis Brems, who was your <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/manual/sunday-school?lang=eng">Sunday School</a> teacher?&rdquo; I told her that I did. She continued, &ldquo;He is now 105 years of age. He lives in a small care center but meets with the entire <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/ensign/2003/05/the-importance-of-the-family?lang=eng">family</a> each Sunday, where he delivers a <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/manual/sunday-school?lang=eng">Sunday School lesson</a>. Last Sunday, Grandpa announced to us, &lsquo;My dears, I am going to die this week. Will you please call Tommy Monson and tell him this. He&rsquo;ll know what to do.&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p56" class="">I visited Brother Brems the very next evening. I could not speak to him, for he was deaf. I could not write a message for him to read, for he was blind. What was I to do? I was told that his family communicated with him by taking the finger of his right hand and then tracing on the palm of his left hand the name of the person visiting and then any message. I followed the procedure and took his finger and spelled on the palm of his hand T-O-M-M-Y M-O-N-S-O-N. Brother Brems became excited and, taking my hands, placed them on his head. I knew his desire was to receive a priesthood blessing. The driver who had taken me to the care center joined me as we placed our hands on the head of Brother Brems and provided the desired blessing. Afterward, tears streamed from his sightless eyes. He grasped our hands, and we read the movement of his lips. The message: &ldquo;Thank you so much.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p57" class="">Within that very week, just as Brother Brems had predicted, he passed away. I received the telephone call and then met with the family as funeral arrangements were made. How thankful I am that a response to render service was not delayed.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p58" class="">The bridge of service invites us to cross over it frequently.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p59" class="">Finally, the Lord provided us the <span class="strong">Bridge of Prayer.</span> He directed, &ldquo;Pray always, and I will pour out my Spirit upon you, and great shall be your blessing.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote13-23911_000_022">13</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p60" class="">I share with you an account described in a mother&rsquo;s letter to me relating to prayer. She wrote:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p61" class="">&ldquo;Sometimes I wonder if I make a difference in my children&rsquo;s lives. Especially as a single mother working two jobs to make ends meet, I sometimes come home to confusion, but I never give up hope.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p62" class="">&ldquo;My children and I were watching a television broadcast of general conference, and you were speaking about prayer. My son made the statement, &lsquo;Mother, you&rsquo;ve already taught us that.&rsquo; I said, &lsquo;What do you mean?&rsquo; And he replied, &lsquo;Well, you&rsquo;ve taught us to pray and showed us how, but the other night I came to your room to ask something and found you on your knees praying to Heavenly Father. If He&rsquo;s important to you, He&rsquo;ll be important to me.&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p63" class="">The letter concluded, &ldquo;I guess you never know what kind of influence you&rsquo;ll be until a child observes you doing yourself what you have tried to teach him to do.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p64" class="">No relating of a prayer touches me so deeply as the prayer offered by Jesus in the Garden of Gethsemane. I believe Luke describes it best:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p65" class="">&ldquo;He &hellip; went &hellip; to the mount of Olives; and his disciples also followed him.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p66" class="">&ldquo;And when he was at the place, he said unto them, Pray that ye enter not into temptation.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p67" class="">&ldquo;And he was withdrawn from them about a stone&rsquo;s cast, and kneeled down, and prayed,</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p68" class="">&ldquo;Saying, Father, if thou be willing, remove this cup from me: nevertheless not my will, but thine, be done.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p69" class="">&ldquo;And there appeared an angel unto him from heaven, strengthening him.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p70" class="">&ldquo;And being in an agony he prayed more earnestly: and his sweat was as it were great drops of blood falling down to the ground.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote14-23911_000_022">14</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p71" class="">In due time came the trek to the cross. What suffering He endured as He made His burdensome way, carrying His own cross. Heard were the words He uttered upon the cross: &ldquo;Father, forgive them; for they know not what they do.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote15-23911_000_022">15</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p72" class="">At length Jesus declared, &ldquo;It is finished: and he bowed his head, and gave up the ghost.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote16-23911_000_022">16</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p73" class="">These events, coupled with His glorious <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/ensign/2000/05/resurrection?lang=eng">Resurrection</a>, completed the final bridge of our trilogy: <span class="strong">The Bridge of Obedience, the Bridge of Service, the Bridge of Prayer.</span></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p74" class="">Jesus, the Bridge Builder, spanned that vast chasm we call death. &ldquo;For as in Adam all die, even so in <a class="no-link-style" href="http://jesuschrist.lds.org/">Christ</a> shall all be made alive.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote17-23911_000_022">17</a>
      </sup> He did for us what we could not do for ourselves; hence, mankind can cross the bridges He built&mdash;into life eternal.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p75" class="">I close by paraphrasing the poem &ldquo;The Bridge Builder&rdquo;:</p>
			<div class="figure">
				<div class="stanza" id="">
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">&ldquo;You have crossed the chasm, deep and wide&mdash;</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">Why build you the bridge at the eventide?&rdquo;</span>
	  </div>
				</div>
				<div class="stanza" id="">
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">&ldquo;There followeth after me today</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">A vast throng whose feet must pass this way.</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">This chasm that has been naught to me</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">To that great throng may a pitfall be.</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">They too must cross in the twilight dim;</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">Good friend, I am building the bridge for them.&rdquo;</span>
	  </div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/2003/11/the-bridge-builder.p84" class="">That we may have the wisdom and determination to cross the bridges the Savior built for each of us is my sincere prayer, in the name of Jesus Christ, amen.</p>
		
                            
                            
